e valid k, we return -1.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 1000\n-1000 <= nums[i] <= 1000\nnums[i] != 0\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findMaxK(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findMaxK(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        num_set = set(nums)\n        max_k = -1\n        \n        for num in nums:\n            if num > 0 and -num in num_set:\n                max_k = max(max_k, num)\n        \n        return max_k\n```\n\nThis solution uses a set to store the numbers for O(1) average time complexity lookups. It iterates through the list of numbers, checking if the current number is positive and if its negative counterpart exists in the set. If both conditions are met, it updates the `max_k` with the maximum value found. If no such pair is found, it returns -1.", "estimated_date": 1665878400000}